title: A Single- and Multiple-Dose Study to Assess the Safety, Tolerability, Pharmacokinetics, and Pharmacodynamics of Single and Multiple Intravenous Doses of LY3002813 in Patients With Mild Cognitive Impairment Due to Alzheimer's Disease or Mild to Moderate Alzheimer's Disease
description_brief:
The study will evaluate the effect of LY3002813 on brain scans. The study will evaluate the safety of LY3002813 by looking at adverse events (side effects). The study will also look at the effect the body has on LY3002813. Study participants will have mild cognitive impairment (MCI) due to AD or mild to moderate AD.

The study involves 3 parts.

* Part A in which participants will receive a single dose of LY3002813 or placebo (no drug).
* Part B in which participants will receive multiple doses of LY3002813 or placebo for 24 weeks.
* Part C in which participants will receive multiple doses of LY3002813 or placebo for up to 72 weeks.

Drug will be given as an intravenous infusion (injection into a vein). For Parts A, B and C, the study will last approximately 72 weeks, not including screening of approximately 56 days. The study is for research purposes only and is not intended to treat any medical condition.

outcomeMeasures.title: Change From Baseline in Florbetapir Positron Emission Tomography (PET) Scan Standard Uptake Value Ratio (SUVr)
outcomeMeasures.description: Florbetapir PET imaging was used to confirm the presence of amyloid pathology consistent with AD. Change from baseline was done to test the hypothesis that amyloid burden was reduced in participants in the treatment group. The change from baseline to the postbaseline visit of the composite summary standard uptake value ratio of florbetapir F18 was calculated. Least square (LS) mean value was controlled for baseline value, baseline age, pooled investigator, treatment and visit. The composite summary measure is an unweighted average of the 6 smaller regions (anterior cingulate, frontal medial orbital, parietal, posterior cingulate, precuneus, and temporal) normalized to whole cerebellum or subject-specific white matter.
outcomeMeasures.populationDescription: All randomized participants who received at least 1 dose of study drug and had baseline and post baseline scan data.

outcomeMeasures.title: Percentage of Participants With Treatment-Emergent Anti-Drug Antibodies (TE-ADAs) to LY3002813
outcomeMeasures.description: Blood samples were tested to determine if a participant reacted to LY3002813 by producing anti-LY3002813 antibodies. Samples were identified as TE-ADAs if the post-treatment sample had an increase of at least 4 fold in titer from pre-treatment values. If the pre-treatment value was not detected or was not present, a 1:20 post-treatment titer was required to indicate treatment emergence. The percentage of participants with TE ADA was calculated as: (the number of participants with TE ADA / total number of participants with at least 1 post-treatment immunogenicity sample analyzed)\*100.
outcomeMeasures.populationDescription: All randomized participants who received at least one dose of study drug \& had least one non-missing test result for ADA for each of the baseline period and the post-baseline period.

explanation_target: Reason: The protocol describes LY3002813 given by intravenous infusion with safety, tolerability, pharmacokinetics and pharmacodynamics as endpoints in participants with MCI due to AD or mild–moderate AD—features consistent with testing a disease-modifying therapy rather than a symptomatic cognitive enhancer or behavioral treatment. (Study title and description provided by user.)

Act: Web verification — LY3002813 is donanemab, a humanized IgG1 monoclonal antibody that targets a pyroglutamate form of amyloid-β in deposited plaques and was developed by Eli Lilly. Donanemab has been studied as an IV-administered anti-amyloid antibody and has shown PET amyloid reductions in trials. citeturn0search1turn0search12turn0search3

Act (trial match): The trial structure (single- and multiple-dose IV, safety/tolerability, PK/PD, and imaging effects on brain scans) matches early-phase testing of a biologic anti-amyloid agent; clinical trial records for LY3002813 (donanemab) show similar designs (single- and multiple-dose IV dosing and PET outcomes). citeturn0search2turn0search1

Reflect: Classification — because LY3002813 is a monoclonal antibody that directly targets Alzheimer pathology (amyloid plaques), the correct category is 'disease-targeted biologic'. There is no indication the agent is a small molecule, a purely symptomatic cognitive enhancer, or a neuropsychiatric symptom treatment. The user-provided description and published trial reports support this classification. citeturn0search1turn0search3
